This method serves as the main entry point for the VulkanRenderer class. It receives a pointer to the GLFWwindow, which will be used to create the surface for rendering. The method calls a series of other methods in the order that they should be created. These other methods will be filled in later as you work through the process of initializing and rendering using Vulkan.

Sure, here is an updated cleanup() method that destroys all Vulkan objects created in the init() method in the reverse order:

```c++
void VulkanRenderer::cleanup() {
    vkDeviceWaitIdle(device);

    cleanupSwapchain();

    vkDestroySemaphore(device, renderFinishedSemaphore, nullptr);
    vkDestroySemaphore(device, imageAvailableSemaphore, nullptr);
    vkDestroyCommandPool(device, commandPool, nullptr);
    for (auto framebuffer : framebuffers) {
        vkDestroyFramebuffer(device, framebuffer, nullptr);
    }
    vkDestroyPipeline(device, graphicsPipeline, nullptr);
    vkDestroyPipelineLayout(device, pipelineLayout, nullptr);
    vkDestroyRenderPass(device, renderPass, nullptr);
    for (auto imageView : swapchainImageViews) {
        vkDestroyImageView(device, imageView, nullptr);
    }
    vkDestroySwapchainKHR(device, swapchain, nullptr);
    vkDestroyDevice(device, nullptr);
    vkDestroySurfaceKHR(instance, surface, nullptr);
    if (callback != VK_NULL_HANDLE) {
        auto DestroyDebugReportCallbackEXT = reinterpret_cast<PFN_vkDestroyDebugReportCallbackEXT>(vkGetInstanceProcAddr(instance, "vkDestroyDebugReportCallbackEXT"));
        DestroyDebugReportCallbackEXT(instance, callback, nullptr);
    }
    vkDestroyInstance(instance, nullptr);
}
```

This method destroys all Vulkan objects created in the init() method in the reverse order. It also waits for the device to finish executing all commands before cleanup begins. Note that the `cleanupSwapchain()` method is called first to ensure that any objects that depend on the swapchain are cleaned up first. This is important to avoid any dependency issues during cleanup.

Sure, here is an example implementation of the createInstance() method that creates a Vulkan instance with application and engine information:

```c++
void VulkanRenderer::createInstance() {
    VkApplicationInfo appInfo = {};
    appInfo.sType = VK_STRUCTURE_TYPE_APPLICATION_INFO;
    appInfo.pApplicationName = "My Vulkan Engine";
    appInfo.applicationVersion = VK_MAKE_VERSION(1, 0, 0);
    appInfo.pEngineName = "My Vulkan Engine";
    appInfo.engineVersion = VK_MAKE_VERSION(1, 0, 0);
    appInfo.apiVersion = VK_API_VERSION_1_2;

    VkInstanceCreateInfo createInfo = {};
    createInfo.sType = VK_STRUCTURE_TYPE_INSTANCE_CREATE_INFO;
    createInfo.pApplicationInfo = &appInfo;

    uint32_t glfwExtensionCount = 0;
    const char** glfwExtensions;

    glfwExtensions = glfwGetRequiredInstanceExtensions(&glfwExtensionCount);

    createInfo.enabledExtensionCount = glfwExtensionCount;
    createInfo.ppEnabledExtensionNames = glfwExtensions;

    createInfo.enabledLayerCount = 0;

    VkResult result = vkCreateInstance(&createInfo, nullptr, &instance);
    if (result != VK_SUCCESS) {
        throw std::runtime_error("Failed to create Vulkan instance");
    }
}
```

This method uses the VkApplicationInfo and VkInstanceCreateInfo structures to specify information about the application and engine when creating the Vulkan instance. It also retrieves the required GLFW extensions and sets them as enabled extensions for the Vulkan instance.

If the vkCreateInstance() call fails, the method throws a std::runtime_error with an appropriate error message.

Sure, here is an example implementation of the createDebugCallback() method that sets up a debug callback for the Vulkan instance using the VK_EXT_debug_report extension:

```c++
void VulkanRenderer::createDebugCallback() {
    if (!enableValidationLayers) {
        return;
    }

    VkDebugReportCallbackCreateInfoEXT createInfo = {};
    createInfo.sType = VK_STRUCTURE_TYPE_DEBUG_REPORT_CALLBACK_CREATE_INFO_EXT;
    createInfo.flags = VK_DEBUG_REPORT_ERROR_BIT_EXT | VK_DEBUG_REPORT_WARNING_BIT_EXT;
    createInfo.pfnCallback = debugCallback;

    auto CreateDebugReportCallbackEXT = reinterpret_cast<PFN_vkCreateDebugReportCallbackEXT>(vkGetInstanceProcAddr(instance, "vkCreateDebugReportCallbackEXT"));
    if (CreateDebugReportCallbackEXT == nullptr) {
        throw std::runtime_error("Failed to find vulkan debug callback function");
    }

    VkResult result = CreateDebugReportCallbackEXT(instance, &createInfo, nullptr, &callback);
    if (result != VK_SUCCESS) {
        throw std::runtime_error("Failed to create vulkan debug callback");
    }
}
```

This method first checks if validation layers are enabled. If not, it just returns to avoid setting up the debug callback.

If validation layers are enabled, it creates a VkDebugReportCallbackCreateInfoEXT structure to hold information about the debug callback to be created, including callback flags and function pointer. It then creates the callback using the instance and the VkDebugReportCallbackCreateInfoEXT structure.

Note the usage of the `reinterpret_cast` function to cast the `CreateDebugReportCallbackEXT` function pointer to the appropriate type. This is necessary because the function signature of the debug callback function is fixed and cannot be modified.

Finally, if the callback creation fails, the method throws a std::runtime_error with an appropriate error message.

